The technological singularity


June 2022



















ABSTRACT—The technological singularity debate is gaining gradually attention in the scientific community, in the media, and in society.
    This technological singularity concept, which has been in our lives for the last 30 years, was first introduced and defined by Professor Vernor Vinge in 1993; This technological revolution has been defined as the machine with a vigilant and superhuman intelligence that will spread faster and more unexpectedly than any technical revolution [1]
    Some futurists, such as Raymond Kurtzweil, who increased the popularity of this subject, claim that the complexity of the world will go far beyond human comprehension with this technological breakthrough which these smart machines will create soon. According to them, it will be impossible for them to predict in which direction the future of the world will continue and what awaits humanity from that day on [2]. 
    The purpose of this report is to review the approaches, parameters and findings of the research conducted on different definitions of the concept of Technological Singularity, to discuss the predictions they reached about the benefits and difficulties in this subject, and to give an opinion on what the limitations of the research are and how they can be improved.
    The assumptions that the Technological Singularity can occur in 3 different ways are the subject of research. The first of these is the invention of a machine with superhuman intelligence, another one is singularity will occur as a result of the cooperation of a user and machine, and the last one is that this singularity will be reached with a revolution to be made of in the field of genetics. The scans for this article include research that assumes the Technological Singularity will occur with the creation of a machine with superhuman intelligence.

Key Words—Singularity, Technological Singularity, Exponential Growth, Mind Steps Theory, Complexity of Evolution, The Basis of Intelligence, Advantages & Limitations of Technological Singularity.










    I. INTRODUCTION
    Some authors and scientists predict that there will be a rapidly approaching technological singularity. In order to clarify what these predictions are, it may be useful to shed light upon on what the concept of singularity means in other sciences.
    "Singularity" was first discussed in Physics by John von Neumann in 1950 as the centres of black holes that we cannot predict how the physical laws will work on it. Although in Mathematics, it is used for the situation where a function increases strictly, and its value goes to infinity [3]. 
    As for the Technological Singularity does not have a meaning accepted by everyone, because the state of affair covers ambiguous broad field and the human brain and intelligence, which are compared, have a complexity that is not yet fully understood; hence there is uncertainty what will be exactly measured and it is not possible to make inferences with insufficient data [4],[5]. 
    Futurists Vinge and Kurzweil define the Technological Singularity as the moment when artificial intelligence surpasses all human intelligences. According to them that the world will go beyond our understanding in an unprecedented way from that moment. Therefore, it will be impossible to predict in which direction the future of the world will continue or what awaits humanity [1],[2].
    II. EXISTING RESEARCH PROJECTS
A. Exponential Growth
    Scientists and authors have different assumptions about the timing of the technological singularity considering different parameters.
    Vernor Vinge; Based on his research trend on the steady and rapid growth of computer technologies published by H. Moravec in 1988, he predicts that the technological singularity may occur in 3 different ways by 2030. He mentions that the first is computer networks will suddenly awaken as a superhuman intelligent entity, second is that users who will master the subject in the computer field can be considered superhuman intelligent, and third is this will happen with a leap that will show itself in the biological field. He assumes it will be impossible to predict what kind of future awaits people with this limitlessness of this hypothetical point that will break the mould of all existences. And he emphasizes that our follow to "Intelligent Amplification" will be playing an active role in bringing this singularity in particular [1],[2],[6]. 
    Likewise, Kurzweil, with an approach inspired by the "Moore's Law" named by Gordon Moore in 1965, claims that the technological singularity will occur in 2045 with a ratio based on the exponential growth of computer technological properties “Fig 1.”, which is an acceleration speed of 20,000 years, “Fig 2.”. He even takes his guesses a further that death itself will be completely eliminated [2].
    So, what are the chances of predictions about the Technological Singularity in both studies? The studies on which Vinge and Kurzweil base their predictions give consistent results in mathematical calculations regarding the increase in the hardware and technological features of computers and reflect a logical exponential growth in itself.
    However, both of these studies; compare the development rate of computer hardware and technologies with concepts such as human and intelligence consisting of intangible and concrete unsolved complexities. These criteria-parameter limitations of these studies reinforce the view that it is unlikely to predict the future of the Technological Singularity in the near future [7]. 
   
    


B. Mind Steps Theory 
    Gerald Hawkins is of the opinion that evolution began with the existence of the world, and that these evolutions were turning points for evolution itself, for the world and for living things. Human beings are in an interaction with the world from the moment they exist, and this interaction plays a major role in shaping the human mind. Thus, that evolution and human continue to create turning points on each other. 
    Hawkins' mind steps theory: From 35,000 BC, it begins with the step of age of chaos, where atoms and molecules exist, which we now know as the big bang theory, and which this step calls "0". Then in turn, that is the emergence of has a memory-enabled and self-replicating DNA, that is, biology. The other is the emergence of the pattern definition of intelligence, this is the period that shows that technology was somehow invented. There is the Age of revolution stage, and finally, it is a period in which the entire universe is saturated with human intelligence, and human unites with everything intelligent and mindless. This assumes that after the first 5 steps, 4 more evolutions awaiting humanity will take place; these are dated to 2021-2045-2051 and 2053. shorter, “Fig. 3”.
    In his theory, the fact that the parameters of the hypothesis are associated with inventions and paradigm shifts in evolutionary processes shows that the research intends to find solid ground. but the presence of dynamic variables in real life, combined with the limitations of research for the hypothesis, makes it difficult to make a firm inference about what the expected date estimates might be [8], [9]. 


C. Complexity of Evolution   
    Complexity Theorist and Physicist Theodore Modis who thinks that technological abilities feed on a complexity and that these complexities create new ones, evaluates the Technological Singularity subject in terms of increasing complexity of the universe. 
    In his empirical research which he analysis evolutionary turning points with using 13 different data sets that they are consistent with each other, he thinks that the pure exponential growth used in analysis that claims the Technological Singularity will soon be achieved may be part of a S-curve which that is a logistic curve. In this regard, he estimates that the world reached its maximum complexity of growth rate around 1990 and that this rate of change will decrease in the context of this research for the future.
    This research, which deals with the hypothetical point of linking the increase in complexity to the increase of things changing and the rate of change analyses the rates of evolutionary complexity changes.
    In this analyse, which reflects a logical consistency; He also has dwelled on the dates when new technological capabilities would emerge, for example, Internet/human genome sequencing in 1997, DNA/transistor/nuclear energy complexity in 1947, and modern physics/car/aircraft in 1902.
    The researcher says that there may not be a technological singularity as Kurzweil mentioned, but he expects it to be around 2038, 2083 and 2152, when new technological innovations show as the next turning points. Therewithal according to him, there cannot be a technological singularity like Kurzweil mentioned [10], [11],[12].

D. The Basis of Intelligence 
    Referring to the fact that intelligence means more than 100 meanings, Cochrane states that a full definition, measure or qualification cannot be found to meet concept of superhuman intelligence used for Technological Singularity.
    This research argues that large complex systems can be fed from linear relationships and that machine intelligence will increase logarithmically or linearly rather than at an assumed exponential rate.
    He is prepared this research by comparing the computational capacity of the human brain with the chaotic distributed and simple linear projections of artificial intelligence. This study, which reflects a mathematical consistency in itself, does not infer a future or definition of Technological Singularity due to the lack of semantic precision of the human intelligence [13]. 
    III. ADVANTAGES AND LIMITATIONS OF TECHNOLOGICAL SINGULARITY
    In case of the realization Technological Singularity, advances in science and technology will be inevitable. These advances cannot only make human life easier, however also provide benefits for a more sustainable world. 
    With progression in genetics, nanotechnology, robotics and artificial intelligence, diseases can be eliminated by restructuring cell structures. Thanks to artificial-organic organs and limbs, the quality of human life can be increased [14], [15]. 
    With the developments to be made in the field of personalized biological science, the potential to generate electricity through the human body can be provided which with it an uninterrupted power can be obtained. Thus, this progress can improve human energy performance, and with it make valuable contributions to human life [16], [17], [18], [19], [20]. 
    At the same time, there are promising approaches to the level of renewable energy production, reducing carbon emissions, protecting biological diversity, producing sustainable energies, measures that can be taken for climate change, environmental problems and climate change [21], [22], [23].
    On the other hand, the technological singularity can be destroying the privacy of personal information [24]. Reducing employment by using machinery instead of manpower can cause unemployment; as a result of this, there may be great decreases in the demand for goods and services that can lead to economic and social collapses [25], [26].
    Due to the inability of ethical practices in countries with less democratic governments, this technological singularity can lead to discrimination and nationalism. In a worse scenario, leaving the whole world in the hands of some companies or individuals with this technology will actually bring along a monopoly process. As Vinge said, it's sure to produce unimaginable results [1].
    IV. CONCLUSION & RECOMENDATIONS
      Technological Singularity is an ambiguous phenomenon that has not yet started practice in today’s world. Therefore, there are different meanings attribute to it. 
    Each of the research reviewed in this report provides mathematically meaningful and reasonable calculations in itself. However, the fact that the complexity of the human brain, which is the parameter of research and comparison is too complex and deep to be copied, and the lack of a definite definition of human intelligence in itself, are the biggest restrictive reasons for the research [27].
     In the field of the Technological Singularity, human intelligence and brain, which are lacking in existing knowledge, need to be resolved in course to arrive at the right judgements and strategies. This is the first of the most important steps that can be taken for the creation of a machine with superhuman intelligence.
    For this, in addition to basic sciences such as neurology, physiology, biology, behavioural sciences, biophysics, biochemistry, psychology, linguistics, clinical sciences such as neuroscience, psychiatry, neuroradiology, interdisciplinary disciplines such as cognitive psychophysiology and neuropsychology, statistics, electrical-electronic engineering, biomedical There is a need for more research to be conducted in applied technical disciplines such as engineering and sociology.
     In addition, time and cost constraints of infrastructure investments and other research-development services (repair, renewal or replacement) were not included in that research projects. Therefore, that greatly reduces the consistency of the research conducted and it shows that the technological singularity will not be possible in the near future [7],[28].   
    On the other hand, with the development of technological capabilities, great benefits can be provided in many different fields for the future of humanity and the world, such as health, environmental regulations, energy management systems, etc. 
    Contrary to advantages. There may be a process of monopolization that Technological Singularity can bring along. Since this poses a great threat to humanity, it is a very sensitive issue that needs to be carefully examined and addressed.
     In addition, risk assessment scans of the risks and benefits of the Technological Singularity, which are thought to have great and profound effects, will be beneficial both in better managing the risks that may occur in the future and in reducing the unpredictable negative effects.










